title: For Sale:  Sten  MK 3 Demilled parts kit and Indianapolis Ordnance Semi-Auto Sten Mk 3 kit
postcontent:
This is not a gun or frearm and does not require an FFL for shipping.

Original WWII British Sten Mk 3 parts kit. This is a parts kit that has been saw-demilled and cannot be reassembled into a working firearm, and so it has been classified as a non-firearm by the BATFE. These parts were hand-selected for minimal wear and abuse. All parts are included except the missing chunks of the receiver tube. Original gun was demilled and packed in Cosmoline after the war, and is thus well preserved and rust free.  Included but not shown are three 32-rd magazines.

The other parts included are a premium Indianapolis Ordnance Semi-Auto parts kit, all new parts, including an 80% completed receiver tube, 16-inch barrel (required by the BATFE), semi-auto bolt and the various pins, springs, rivets, and small parts required to complete the kit. To be very clear, the new receiver tube CANNOT BE USED WITH THE ORIGINAL BOLT. It is designed with a vertical magazine mount and has ventilation holes already drilled. The bolt kit is for a vertical magazine mount and is designed to fit the receiver tube. The receiver tube has a plan decal attached for ease of use. Instructions are included.

I bought these parts with the intention of doing the disassembly of the Sten and building a semi-auto Sten based on the 80% receiver, which is of course perfectly legal. Then I realized I don't have the time to complete it so I'm taking a bit of a loss to get the parts out of my project to-do list. If you have time to do it, this would be a great project.  If you have a Dremel Tool and some patience, you can do it.

I can ship in the 50 US States (shipping extra, please pay the total by US Postal MO and I'll ship when it clears) or local pickup in the Tampa area (cash payment OK) is great.

postcontent:
Rebluing is more than restoring the color of your gun.  It's a complete overhaul.  We start by completely disassembling the gun.  Then the gun is buffed completely to remove any scratches or rust pits and restoring all corners and edges to "factory new" sharpness.  Then it's polished to a bright luster for better appearance.  The gun is then boiled in a special solution which removes every trace of dirt, and blued to a deep black color.  Finally we reassemble and function test the gun.  The result is a gun which in most cases looks "better than new".
